briefdescription.para: Return the current time in system-dependent units.

detaileddescription.para: The current time is returned as a number of "ticks", where each tick represents some system-dependent amount of time. The resolution of the timing routines varies, but on all systems, it is well under one microsecond. The cost of this routine is in the 10s-to-100s of nanoseconds on GHz class machines.

briefdescription.para: Get a "start" tick time for measuring an interval of time, followed by a later call to ArchGetStopTickTime().

detaileddescription.para: Or see ArchIntervalTimer. This is like ArchGetTickTime but it includes compiler & CPU fencing & reordering constraints in an attempt to get the best measurement possible.

briefdescription.para: Get a "stop" tick time for measuring an interval of time.

detaileddescription.para: See ArchGetStartTickTime() or ArchIntervalTimer. This is like ArchGetTickTime but it includes compiler & CPU fencing & reordering constraints in an attempt to get the best measurement possible.

Although the number of ticks per second may be very large, on many current systems the tick timers do not update at that rate. Rather, sequential calls to ArchGetTickTime() may report increases of 10s to 100s of ticks, with a minimum increment betwewen calls. This function returns that minimum increment as measured at startup time.

Note that if this value is of sufficient size, then short times measured with tick timers are potentially subject to significant noise. In particular, an interval of measured tick time is liable to be off by +/- one ArchGetTickQuantum().

briefdescription.para: Return the ticks taken to record an interval of time with ArchIntervalTimer, as measured at startup time.
Convert a duration measured in "ticks", as returned by ArchGetTickTime(), to nanoseconds.
Convert a duration measured in "ticks", as returned by ArchGetTickTime(), to seconds.
Convert a duration in seconds to "ticks", as returned by ArchGetTickTime().

detaileddescription.para: Useful when converting ticks obtained from ArchTickTime()

briefdescription.para: Run fn repeatedly attempting to determine a consensus fastest execution time with low noise, for up to maxTicks, then return the consensus fastest execution time.

detaileddescription.para: If a consensus is not reached in that time, return a best estimate instead. If reachedConsensus is not null, set it to indicate whether or not a consensus was reached. This function ignores maxTicks greater than 5 billion ticks and runs for up to 5 billion ticks instead. The fn will run for an indeterminate number of times, so it should be side-effect free. Also, it should do essentially the same work on every invocation so that timing its execution makes sense.
